Abdul Qadeer Khan, known as the father of the Pakistani atomic bomb, supplied highly enriched uranium to Iran in 2001, potentially aiding Iran's nuclear ambitions.
Khan admitted to nuclear leaks to Iran, Libya, and North Korea.
Reports suggest that Libya could have developed nuclear weapons quickly with the uranium plant provided by Khan.
Investigations revealed a South African scheme to deliver a uranium enrichment plant to Libya.
Despite claims of collaboration with the US, Pakistan denied assisting in targeting Iranian nuclear sites.
The International Atomic Energy Agency continues to probe Iran's nuclear activities amid concerns of clandestine weapons programs.
Pakistan has defended its efforts to prevent nuclear technology leaks
